__ro__ People returning to work after a career break : I call them relaunchers .
__ro__ These are people who have taken career breaks for elder care , for childcare reasons , pursuing a personal interest or a personal health issue .
__ro__ Closely related are career transitioners of all kinds : veterans , military spouses , retirees coming out of retirement or repatriating expats .
__ro__ Returning to work after a career break is hard because of a disconnect between the employers and the relaunchers .
__ro__ Employers can view hiring people with a gap on their resume as a high-risk proposition , and individuals on career break can have doubts about their abilities to relaunch their careers , especially if they &apos;ve been out for a long time .
__ro__ This disconnect is a problem that I &apos;m trying to help solve .
__ro__ Now , successful relaunchers are everywhere and in every field .
__ro__ This is Sami Kafala .
__ro__ He &apos;s a nuclear physicist in the UK who took a five-year career break to be home with his five children .
__ro__ The Singapore press recently wrote about nurses returning to work after long career breaks .
__ro__ And speaking of long career breaks , this is Mimi Kahn .
__ro__ She &apos;s a social worker in Orange County , California , who returned to work in a social services organization after a 25-year career break .
__ro__ That &apos;s the longest career break that I &apos;m aware of .
__ro__ Supreme Court Justice Sandra Day O &apos;Connor took a five-year career break early in her career .
__ro__ And this is Tracy Shapiro , who took a 13-year career break .
__ro__ Tracy answered a call for essays by the Today Show from people who were trying to return to work but having a difficult time of it .
